When an associate accesses a website/URL unfamiliar to Walmart a Notifiaction page is displayed letting the associate know the site has not been approved to view. A Ticket is automatically generated in Service Now. Then an associate has to copy the URL and go to the McAfee Security website to see if the url is categorized and the level of security the site has and based off of bith of those validation they determine whether to release the website to be viewable or to place a block on it and then notify the associate and their manager of the access of the site.

We have recently consolidated the reconciliation process for all lease accounts for all markets to a consolidated level.  Our reconciliation is performed between three lease systems and the GL.  Each market is on a separate instance and multiple reports must be pulled for each market, as a result we pull a combined 80 reports to perform this reconciliation.  It takes roughly 6 hours each month to pull all reports.  More importantly, this is done at at month-end close and is time sensitive.  We need to automate this process to free up these crucial hours for our team to perform other needed functions and accelerate the completion of our recon so issues can be identified and addressed timely.
comments:
Hey Matthew, I think we’re going to have to table this one.  We were going to try and automate the pulling of a large volume of reports from Nakisa, our new non-real estate lease system.  However, after talking to the project lead, she informed us that, due to the new nature of the system, which is still experiencing a fairly large volume of patches, updates, changes to reporting language, etc, it would not make sense to try and setup a bot to pull reports yet.  We plan to look into this again sometime next year once the system is more stable.
Blake Jones Sr. Manager, Global Leases  Cell: 918.886.3189

description: We just want to see what our options could be. We deal with information on our own secure SIRT network that would need to be handled with diligence.

The high level overview of what we are trying to solve:
1)	We have a Power BI dashboard that we want to leverage for our daily AM reporting
2)	We need to find a sustainable way to refresh the data, export it to PDF, and attach it to an email

We know that the Power BI dashboard can be scheduled to refresh systemically. We know that a PDF can be created and attached to an email manually. We are not aware of any way to systemically export the Dashboard to a PDF. We are thinking that since this is a simple manual process involving a few mouse clicks within Power BI, this may be a good use case for RPA. Would you have a few minutes in the coming days to talk through this with us?

The current excel based process is no longer sustainable - we continue to have process errors that require manual intervention 7 days a week starting as early as 530 am. The ability to solve the Power BI challenges will also aid in our transition to the GDP Data Lake reporting dashboard by bridging the gap between current reporting views and future state.

description: This request is for the $1-a-day college program announced this year. A rough draft of the process placemat is attached for reference. In short, we are looking to automate an audit process for reimbursement requests received from Guild Education, our education partner, on behalf of participating associates. Data received via the Tumbleweed server needs to be checked against a set of control parameters to ensure authenticity of the request, such as duplicate or high amounts. The process uses incoming data and historical data kept on Data Lake to validate the request. Approved requests are forwarded to Payroll for processing and payment. Flagged requests require a secondary, manual review for approval or denial. As there are over 1000 associates enrolled in the first semester and each can submit several reimbursement requests, automating this process will save valuable time. Further, an automated process will all associates to receive their reimbursement sooner, which limits a potential financial hardship.

description:
Walmart.com allows customers to receive a partial refund (adjustment) if an item they purchased subsequently goes down in price. The business case for doing this is to avoid customers returning their item to a Walmart store or Returns Center and re-purchasing at the lower price (with subsequent handling cost of the return)

Customers have been signing up to third party solution providers who monitor their purchases and the online prices of those they shop with. There are two providers we identified as significant volume for Walmart Customer Care, "Paribus" and "Earny"

Customer care receives an average of 7200 template formatted email requests from Earny, and 3800 from Paribus. At 11k per week on average, with a handling time of 3.58 (decimal) minutes, the savings achieved by fully automating the process in a future state equates to 657 hours/week, or 34k hours annualized (over $500k at agent hourly cost rate)

Most of the process is very clearly defined already (no gray area) and we are working to finalize clarity on the way we handle Bulk Buyer definition/logic so as much of the $500k can be successfully realized.

In addition, we are collating the "standard text" used for responding to customers who are "denied" the requested adjustment.

The current process map is attached for information. We can discuss/walk thru the info on it.
name: 9200 Price Reduction Requests Process Eccomerce Customer Care
